DialogEval: A Benchmark for Cross-Framework Annotation of LLMs

Evaluating whether models can reason between, behind, and beyond classroom discourse.

ACL 2026 Submission Anonymous Project Page Classroom Dialogue · Reasoning · Evaluation
Paper (PDF) Code & Data (Release)

Abstract

Automated Classroom Dialogue Encoding (ACDE) is critical for understanding instructional quality and supporting pedagogical improvement. However, existing evaluations of large language models (LLMs) often treat classroom discourse as a shallow text classification task, overlooking the deep inferential structures embedded in authentic educational interaction.

We propose DialogEval, a benchmark that evaluates LLMs’ discourse decoding capabilities through the Three Bs framework, examining whether models can reason between the words (contextual dependencies), behind the words (latent pedagogical intent), and beyond the words (sociocultural norms and domain assumptions). Eight representative LLMs are evaluated across three canonical discourse frameworks—FIAC, IRF, and SEDA—covering quantitative, structural, and sociocultural traditions.

Our results reveal a Logic Threshold for contextual reasoning, demonstrate that logic-driven reasoning scaffolds outperform dense rule manuals, and uncover systematic failures such as Domain Rigidity, Expertise Reversal, and Conceptual Granularity Collapse. DialogEval provides both a robust benchmark and diagnostic tools for future research on reasoning-oriented educational LLMs.

Contribution Snapshot

DialogEval is designed as a diagnostic benchmark for educational discourse decoding—measuring not only performance, but also the cognitive failure modes behind model errors.

A Unified Three Bs Framework

We operationalize discourse understanding into Between, Behind, and Beyond the Words, forming a principled cognitive gradient for ACDE evaluation.

Cross-Framework Benchmarking

We evaluate models across FIAC, IRF, and SEDA—representing quantitative interaction, linguistic structure, and sociocultural reasoning traditions—under a shared protocol.

Context-Aware Sliding Window Protocol

A five-turn window labels only the center turn, providing sufficient local context while avoiding long-context distraction.

Failure-Mode Diagnostics

We introduce qualitative tools (confusion matrices, lure-word analysis, RER) that reveal why models fail (e.g., semantic anchoring, schema interference), not just how often.

The Three Bs Framework

From surface labels to cognitive decoding: DialogEval conceptualizes ACDE as a hierarchy of inferential demands.

Between the Words

Contextual Logic

Tests whether models can resolve local contextual dependencies and functional sequences (e.g., IRF structures), rather than labeling isolated sentences.

Behind the Words

Pedagogical Intent

Probes whether models can infer latent instructional intentions and examines how prompting density shapes intent decoding (rule-driven vs. logic-driven strategies).

Beyond the Words

Sociocultural Norms

Examines how domain knowledge, disciplinary logic, and geocultural priors reshape interpretation, revealing schema-driven errors (e.g., domain rigidity).

Figure 1: The ACDE Three Bs framework and its cognitive gradient. The framework decomposes discourse decoding into Between (contextual dependency and functional linkage), Behind (latent pedagogical intent and cognitive load effects), and Beyond the words (domain/geocultural effects and subject moderation), highlighting diagnostic hypotheses such as the Logic Threshold, More-is-Less paradox, and Domain Rigidity.

Benchmark Construction

DialogEval is built on a curated classroom discourse corpus designed to balance ecological validity and analytical rigor.

  • Source pool: 810 classroom sessions (compulsory education).
  • Selection: 20 expert-verified high-quality lessons (10 Arts, 10 Science).
  • Transcription: automated ASR + manual correction; speaker roles labeled.
  • Ground truth: dual annotation (FIAC/IRF/SEDA) with expert adjudication; strong inter-rater reliability (Cohen’s κ).

This benchmark evaluates models against expert-level discourse interpretation rather than simplified proxies.

Framework Coverage

FIAC (Low-inference)
Quantifies observable classroom talk behaviors (teacher talk, student talk, silence).
IRF (Mid-inference)
Tests structural dependencies in initiation–response–feedback chains, including mixed turns (F+I).
SEDA (High-inference)
Targets socio-cognitive functions in knowledge co-construction (invite, build, position, connect, reflect, etc.).

Methodology

DialogEval uses a shared protocol—sliding window context + hierarchical prompting—to test discourse decoding across frameworks.

Sliding Window Context Modeling

Classroom discourse is inherently sequential. To resolve local ambiguity without long-context distraction, DialogEval adopts a five-turn sliding window. The model receives two preceding and two following utterances as context, but must label only the center utterance.

Figure 2: Context-aware sliding window protocol (window size = 5). The model labels the center turn while using its surrounding turns as local context. The window shifts by one turn to traverse the full classroom dialogue sequence.

Hierarchical Prompting

  1. P1 — Vanilla (Zero-shot): category names only.
  2. P2 — Definition (Zero-shot): category + definitions.
  3. P3 — Expert Manual (Few-shot): category + definitions + examples.
  4. P4 — Chain-of-Thought: explicit reasoning paths (logic-driven scaffold).

This hierarchy tests whether reasoning processes outperform rule accumulation under increasing cognitive demand.

Model Zoo

We evaluate representative reasoning-oriented, general-purpose scaled, and education-specific domain models under the same protocol.

Metrics

We report Macro-F1 and Cohen’s Kappa to address class imbalance and measure agreement beyond chance.

Diagnostics

Confusion matrices and lure-word analysis reveal functionally similar categories and lexical triggers that induce systematic errors.

Key Findings

DialogEval highlights not only which models perform well, but which cognitive mechanisms are required—and where models systematically fail.

Finding 1: The Logic Threshold

Resolving contextual dependencies in IRF requires explicit reasoning scaffolds; scaling alone is insufficient to guarantee structural consistency.

Finding 2: Process Over Rules

Dense rule manuals can trigger cognitive overload, while logic-driven Chain-of-Thought prompting provides a more reliable path to correct intent decoding.

Finding 3: Domain Rigidity & Expertise Reversal

Domain-specific models may underperform in novel frameworks, where prior schemas interfere with instruction following and induce proactive inhibition.

Finding 4: Conceptual Granularity Failure

In high-inference SEDA tasks, models often collapse fine-grained socio-cognitive categories into coarse labels, indicating limits in deep pedagogical reasoning.

Figure 3: Confusion matrix on IRF (Qwen2.5-32B). The model frequently confuses pure feedback with mixed turns (F+I), illustrating boundary segmentation failure in structured classroom exchanges.

Figure 4: Confusion matrix on IRF (DeepSeek-R1). Despite stronger reasoning capability, the model still exhibits systematic confusions among initiation, feedback, and mixed turns, reflecting persistent semantic anchoring under contextual ambiguity.

Figure 5: Confusion matrix on FIAC (Gemini-2.0-flash). The matrix reveals category-specific confusions (e.g., student response vs. student initiation), highlighting the role of surface cues in low-inference classroom behavior coding.

Figure 6: Confusion matrix on SEDA clusters (InnoSpark). High-inference categories are frequently mapped into broader “Multiple” or adjacent functional clusters, indicating conceptual granularity collapse in socio-cognitive discourse coding.

Figure 7: Confusion matrix on SEDA clusters (GPT-4o-mini). Errors concentrate in high-inference functions (e.g., positioning, connecting, reflecting), reflecting the difficulty of decoding latent socio-cognitive intent beyond surface semantics.

Capillary Analysis: Lure Words & Cognitive Bias

Beyond aggregated scores, DialogEval diagnoses error mechanisms by linking misclassifications to high-risk lexical triggers.

We define Relative Error Risk (RER) to quantify whether a lexical item disproportionately increases the chance of error within a category:

$$\mathrm{RER}(w,c)=\frac{P(\mathrm{Error}\mid w\in u_t,\ \mathrm{label}=c)}{P(\mathrm{Error}\mid \mathrm{label}=c)}$$

This “capillary” view reveals how models fall back to shortcuts such as instructional fillers, evaluative anchors, and connectors—often overriding deeper functional interpretation.

Figure 8: A pathway view of lexical triggers and misclassification types. Instructional fillers and deictics can trigger hallucinated interactivity; evaluative anchors can induce semantic anchoring; and discourse markers can blur structural boundaries, leading to boundary segmentation failures in IRF-style coding.

Figure 9: Top lure words driving specific misclassifications (ranked by risk multiplier). Different model–framework pairs show distinct lexical sensitivities, supporting the hypothesis that surface triggers can activate pre-existing schemas and produce systematic errors.

Hallucinated Interactivity

Surface fillers (e.g., “here”, “how”) can activate an over-sensitive agency schema, producing false initiation predictions under silence or low-content turns.

Semantic Anchoring

Models over-weight evaluative markers (e.g., “precise”, “indeed”) and misread discourse function, failing to track the exchange-level logic.

Boundary Segmentation Failure

Connectors and markers (e.g., “also”, “for example”, “isn’t it?”) blur functional boundaries, increasing feedback–initiation mixing errors in IRF coding.
